node.text: Being a millionaire may be more common than you think. About 20 million people in the U.S. have enough assets to fit the definition, according to a 2020 study by Credit Suisse. Chris Hogan, author of the book “Everyday Millionaires,” surveyed more than 10,000 of those wealthy individuals to figure out their secret to success. Having a particular mindset almost universally contributed to millionaires’ success, Hogan said. He found that around 97% of millionaires surveyed believed they were in control of their own destiny. That is much higher than the 55% of the general population Hogan found to hold the same opinion. Check out this video to see the other four beliefs and practices that more than 90% of millionaires apply to their money.

node.title: More than 90% of millionaires used these five tools to build wealth

node.text: Americans are funding their retirement accounts at record rates. But figuring out how much your monthly contributions will be worth in a few decades can be confusing. As a rule of thumb, most financial advisors suggest that you save 10% to 15% of your salary. But if your goal is to get to $1 million, the percentage you need to invest will vary drastically based on how old you are when you start. Here's how you can make it happen.

node.text: Investments in farmland are growing across the country as people, including the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates, look for new ways to grow their money. In 2020, Gates made headlines for becoming the largest private farmland owner in the U.S. He had accumulated more than 269,000 acres of farmland across 18 states in less than a decade. His farmland grows onions, carrots and even the potatoes that are used to make McDonald’s french fries. How is he making money off of farmland in the U.S.? Watch the video to find out.

node.title: Why the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates are investing in U.S. farmland

node.text: Porsche is in the minds of many the ultimate sports car brand. Its cars – especially its legendary 911 – blend high performance with quality construction and even a solid reputation for dependability. But the brand that made its name with small nimble two-door sports cars ruffled feathers in the automotive world when it tried its hand at a four-door sport utility vehicle, the Cayenne. Today, SUVs make up a huge chunk of Porsche’s sales. The brand is now entering the race toward electrification – but this time the innovator is playing catch-up to others.

node.title: How Porsche went from sports cars to SUVs ... and EVs

node.text: It’s taken over two years, but these days Jeremy Mateo is finally feeling at home. Mateo, 27, is a real estate broker in Honolulu, Hawaii, and bought his first condo on Oahu island right before the coronavirus pandemic in March 2020. Over the course of a year he saved $60,000 for a down payment and worked toward his goal of buying his “dream home.” Then he spent another year renovating and furnishing his place. The last of his furniture arrived in spring 2021, finally closing the chapter on his homebuying journey. Here’s how Mateo bought his one-bedroom condo for $560,000. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.text:
🙁🌲⁠
⁠
Almost 30% of tree species in the wild are now at risk of extinction, with a wide range of factors responsible for their decline, according to a new analysis.⁠
⁠
The State of the World’s Trees report found that out of the planet’s 58,497 recorded tree species, 17,510 — or 29.9% — were threatened. In addition, 4,099 are regarded as being “possibly threatened” while at least 142 species are now extinct in the wild, according to the report.⁠
⁠
What number of actions that could be taken to “protect and bring back threatened species?" Link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 03, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'A neuroscientist shares the 6 exercises she does every day to build resilience and mental strength CNBC'.

node.text:
When @CNBCMakeIt contributor Wendy Suzuki first began researching anxiety in her lab as a neuroscientist, she never thought of herself as an anxious person. That is, until she started noticing the words used by her subjects, colleagues, friends and even herself to describe how they were feeling — “worried,” “on edge,” stressed out,” “distracted,” “nervous,” “ready to give up.”⁠
⁠
But what she's found over the years is that the most powerful way to combat anxiety is to consistently work on building your resilience and mental strength.⁠
⁠
Find out how you can do that at the link in bio.

node.text: Walmart said Thursday that it is raising the hourly wages for more than 565,000 store workers by at least $1, as the retail industry faces a tight labor market going into the holiday shopping season. Walmart U.S. Chief Executive John Furner said in a memo to staff that this marks the third investment the company has made in salaries in the past year. Walmart’s U.S. average hourly wage is now $16.40, he said. Read more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 03, 2021. May be an image of ‎text that says '‎The original "Doge" meme sold as an NFT for $4 million- now you can own a piece of it for less than $1 WOW curreney noop WOW 0s هd SESES CNBC‎'‎.

node.text:
The legendary “Doge” meme from 2010, which portrays a shiba inu dog named Kabosu and inspired the creation of cryptocurrency dogecoin, sold for $4 million as an NFT, in June. ⁠
⁠
To some, that may seem like a lot of money to pay to own a jpeg, but the “Doge” meme has generated a massive online community, and dogecoin is now a top cryptocurrency by market value. Though most investors couldn’t afford a multimillion-dollar price tag for the “Doge” meme NFT, anyone will now have an opportunity to own a piece of it for as little as less than $1.⁠
⁠
Find out how at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 03, 2021. May be an image of phone and text that says 'Apple could sell 1.5 million electric cars by 2030, Bernstein speculates rI CNBC'.

node.text:
New for subscribers: If Apple releases an electric vehicle by 2025, investment firm Bernstein speculates the company could sell 1.5 million cars by 2030.⁠
⁠
Bernstein characterized the estimate as “an aggressive forecast,” but said the sales estimate would add roughly $75 billion in revenue and effectively double Apple’s overall growth rate. ⁠
⁠
Read about why Bernstein says Apple would be a " formidable" competitor in the auto industry at the link in bio. (Check out CNBC Pro for 7 days for free!)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 02, 2021. May be an image of sky and text that says 'Unvaccinated students who attended spring break led Covid outbreak at University of Chicago, CDC study shows CNBC'.

node.text:
New Covid-19 cases increased rapidly at the University of Chicago this year after students, most of whom were not fully vaccinated, returned from spring break, according to a new CDC study.⁠
⁠
Despite several prevention strategies at the university, such as weekly testing for students living on campus, 158 Covid cases were diagnosed among undergraduate students between March 15 and May 3, according to the new study. Among 140 infected students who were interviewed, 89 said they recently traveled outside of Chicago during spring break, and 57 attended an unmasked indoor social gathering, such as a dinner or party, the agency said.⁠
⁠
Where did these students go for spring break? Link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 02, 2021. May be a cartoon of text that says 'A fake Banksy NFT sold for more than $300,000. Then the buyer got his his money back F CNBC'.

node.text:
The website of street artist Banksy briefly directed users to an auction for a work of digital art that sold for more than $300,000. The problem? It wasn’t authentic.⁠
⁠
Anyone who clicked on the Banksy NFT web page Tuesday would be directed to a link for an auction for a collectible called “Great Redistribution of the Climate Change Disaster.” The page was added to Banksy’s site Tuesday morning and later deleted, stoking speculation that the site may have been hacked. The listing, posted on the OpenSea marketplace, ended early with the NFT selling for 100 ethereum tokens, worth around $336,000 at the time.⁠
⁠
In a strange twist, all of the money was later returned to the buyer. Link in bio to read more about scammers exploiting NFTs.

⁠⁠

President Joe Biden on Thursday blasted the Supreme Court justices who rejected an effort by abortion-rights advocates to stop Texas’ restrictive abortion law from taking effect.⁠
⁠
Biden also directed White House legal and policy officials to respond to the court’s decision by looking into ways for federal agencies to “ensure that women in Texas have access to safe and legal abortions as protected by [Roe v. Wade.]″⁠
⁠
Full details on Texas' new abortion law at the link in bio.

node.text:
Do you have more than 10,000 followers on Twitter? Then you can cash in. 💸⁠
⁠
Twitter on Wednesday launched Super Follows, a feature that allows select users to charge others for access to subscriber-only content. This new feature will finally allow the company’s most popular users to generate revenue from their followers, but access to Super Follows is limited.⁠
⁠
Find out how you can qualify and apply for access to set up your account for Super Follows at the link in bio.

node.text:
Summer travel season is fading – and it's driving down airfares and raising questions about demand in the coming weeks when business travel would normally pick up.⁠
⁠
The TSA screened nearly 1.35 million people on Tuesday, the fewest since May 11. Travel demand usually falls in late summer as children return to school, but airline executives at Frontier, Southwest, American and Spirit last month warned that they would miss revenue or profit forecasts because of weaker bookings, a trend they blamed on rising cases of the delta variant of Covid-19.⁠
⁠
Just how low are fares getting? Find out at the link in bio.
